    # ── virtual environment ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

288
00:20:37,030 --> 00:20:42,240
Before we install all these dependencies,
let's set up our virtual environment.

289
00:20:42,240 --> 00:20:47,280
A virtual environment is an isolated
Python workspace for each project.

290
00:20:47,280 --> 00:20:49,120
Here is why it's essential.

291
00:20:49,930 --> 00:20:53,170
Let's say we have two projects
that needs different version.

292
00:20:53,280 --> 00:20:59,400
Say, pip install Django 3.2 and…
What happens is that when we install

293
00:20:59,410 --> 00:21:05,950
Django 5.0, this replaces the Django
3.2 because we are using a global

294
00:21:05,990 --> 00:21:08,480
Python environment that is system-wide.

295
00:21:08,510 --> 00:21:13,789
For instance, when Django 3.2 is
installed for project A, it works.

296
00:21:14,550 --> 00:21:19,510
However, at a later time, when Django
5.0 is installed for project B, it

297
00:21:19,570 --> 00:21:24,740
overrides that of the project A because
only one version can exist globally.

298
00:21:25,680 --> 00:21:28,170
The solution to this is
the virtual environment.

299
00:21:29,100 --> 00:21:35,698
Each project gets its own
environment Project A has a venv

300
00:21:36,018 --> 00:21:42,448
that houses the Django 3.2, while
project B has its own Django 5.0.

301
00:21:43,028 --> 00:21:44,208
They don't interfere.

302
00:21:44,438 --> 00:21:47,217
Each project has its own isolated Python.

303
00:21:48,087 --> 00:21:52,968
So the-- we can say that the real
problems that the virtual environment

304
00:21:52,968 --> 00:21:58,618
solve are the version conflicts,
the permission errors, and the team

305
00:21:58,618 --> 00:22:01,637
collaboration, and can go as small…

306
00:22:02,387 --> 00:22:03,997
And the team collaboration issue.

307
00:22:04,847 --> 00:22:11,308
Now, you can use UV to create your virtual
environment automatically using uv venv.

308
